default3
default.  In my view, the proposed changes
default to legal aid
default are a serious thre
defaultat to the rule of law
default.  They will, if introduced, undermine
default the right of
default access to justice
default: 
default in particular, access to justice to challenge improper state action, for some of society's most vulnerable people, and those most vulnerable to abuse of state power (for example, those in its custody).
default4
default.  
defaultTh
defaulte
default declared premise of the 
defaultTransforming Legal Ai
defaultd Proposals 
default&#xad;
default 
defaultis 
defaultthat a fair justice system with 'fair outcomes' is essential in our democratic society, and that legal aid is the 'hallmark of a fair, open justice system'.
default  The same has long been recognised by the European Court of Human Rights and other
default European constitutional courts
default.   Access to legal aid as a gateway to access to justice  is especially important when litigation is brought by a subject of st
defaultate action, to challenge the legality of it
default.   Since 
default 
defaultjudicial review is the means by which cour
defaultts restrain the executive when it acts outside the law, access to judicial review is essential to the rule of law and executive accountability.
default5.   The Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 
default(LASPO) 
defaultalready severely limits legal aid fo
defaultr judicial review.  The government acknowledges that the scope for further savings is very small.  Nevertheless, only eight days after LASPO came into force, the Ministry of Justice published proposals which would further remove legal aid for judicial 
defaultrevi
defaultew, in ways and to a point at which would undermine the effective availability of judicial review and its constitutional purpose
default.
default  These changes have not been significantly amended, in response to overwhelming concern expressed in response to the consulta
defaulttion.
default6
default.  
defaultA serious feature of the proposals is their intention to remove access to legal aid (and by necessary implication, access to the courts) for groups of people defined by status.   
defaultA
defaultnother serious feature is their apparent 'ideological' 
defaultopposition 
defaultto
default judicial review which underpin
defaults the proposed changes
default, and the apparent desire to put much state activity beyond court scrutiny by way of judicial review
default.   It has not been disputed that the measures will
default, even on the Ministry of Justice's most 
defaultoptimistic view, save very little (£6 million).  Careful figures illustrating that the 'reforms' will
default cost far more than they will save
default have not been disputed
default.  (Indeed the cost of implementing a test where a recipient of legal aid services must prove a pe
defaultriod of past lawful residence will be almost unworkably complex and costly).  
default7.  
defaultThe 
default principal purpose of the civil legal aid proposals appears to be the 
defaultSecretary of State's intention to cut down on use of judicial review
default.  However, the means chosen to
default achieve this end are not aimed at the cases with low prospects of success, but at particular categories of case, chosen by reference to characteristics of intended litigants, and measures which will prevent 
defaultany 
default case, no matter how meritorious, from being
default pursued at a profit. Public statements by the Secretary of State indicate that he perceives judicial review to be 
defaultimproperl
defaulty used as a tool of political opposition.    This is 
defaultbased on a misunderstanding of the approach taken by the courts, which are astu
defaultte to 
defaultkeep within their proper constitutional realm, but are an essential check upon misuse of public power where it is exercised unlawfully or improperly.
default7
default.  
defaultThe proposals - particularly when read in conjunction with the parallel consultation 
defaultJudicial Re
defaultview: Proposals for Further Reform 
default (6 September 2013)  mean that the base of specialist legal suppliers of social welfare law is likely to be removed.   
defaultThese are not 'fat-cat' lawyers: the equity partners in many successful London legal aid practices are
default paid less than teachers or senior nurses.   
defaultThe proposed legal aid changes are likely to lead to whole-sale exit from the market, and the experience and expertise lost  will not, therefore, be capable of being replaced  if, 
defaultas seems likely, 
defaultmany suppliers
default cease to provide
default such services altogether 
defaultin the light of the proposed
default changes
default.
default8.  The 
defaultobvious adverse impact of the 
defaultproposals 
defaultfor operation of our justice system has
default generated serious concern across the profession, including from 
defaultthose who act primarily
default 
defaultfor 
default public authorities
default, and judges
default.
default It is not insignificant that former House of Lords and Supreme Court judges have expressed themselves in such anxious terms in relation to the proposals
default.  Lord Brown (a former Treasury Devil) questioned whether the p
defaultroposals were compatible with the Lord Chancellor's duties under section 1 Constitutional Reform Act; Lord Hope (the recently retired Vice President of the Supreme Court) said that 
default              
default"I find it hard to believe that a government which truly respected the ru
defaultle of law - 
default              
defaultwhich had taken the trouble to understand what that phrase really means, and to 
default              
defaultstudy the
default 
defaultconsequences of what it has in mind - would have contemplated 
default              
defaultintroducing the [civil legal aid proposals]".
defaultLord Scott said that respect for the rule of law is 
default"cultural ... it is not to be found in every country and it is not immutable. ... Respect for the rule of law is capable of being forfeited and lost if excessive cuts are made affecting potential litigan
defaultts .. It cannot be taken fo
defaultr granted by the Government that that will not happen and I hope they will keep that in mind".
default9.   It is also almost inconceivable that the government's proposals are compatible with EU law
default (Article 47 of the Charter of Rights),
default Articles 6 and 14 of the European Convention on Human Rights
default and Article 15 of the UN Convention on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women
default.  Adoption of these proposals 
defaultwould undermine the existence 
defaultof the justice system which our constitutional 
defaulttradition and our international law obligations demand.
default10.   In short, the implications of the proposals to ref
defaultorm civil legal aid
default amount, in many cases, to effective removal of access to 
defaultmechanisms of redress against unlawful state action
default.  The
default 
defaultproposals
default 
defaultundermine 
defaultacc
defaultess to justice
default, public accountability and the rule of law.  These 
defaultform 
default the
default roots of a democratic society
default, and the proposals, in undermining these, undermine democracy
default.  
default&#xa0;defaultTHE RESIDENCE TESTdefault11.  The proposal is to exclude from  civil legal 
defaultaid
default eligibility
default those who cannot show twelve months lawful residence and those not lawfully present in the United Kingdom.    Note that the onus will be on the person seeking help - perhaps urgently - to demonstrate
default eligibility
default, by
default providing documentary pr
defaultoof
default.
default   Anyone who cannot demonstrate the requisite period of lawful residence 
default 
defaultwill be unable to access legal advice or representation, no matter how 
defaulturgent or 
defaultacute their need for help
default.
default12.  The
default proposal
default to introduce a residence test
default undermines the
default principle of equality before the law:  
default"Every person within the jurisdiction enjoys the equal protection of our laws.   There is no distinction between British nationals and others.  He who is subject to English law 
defaultis entitled to its protection"
default per Lo
defaultrd Scarman in 
defaultKhjawaja 
default [1984] AC 74 at 111G. 
default13.
default  T
defaulthe proposed exceptions to application of the residence test are very narrow, and leave many obvious injustices and lacunae.   
default14.  
defaultContrary to some media reports, 
default 
defaultno 
default general exception 
defaultis proposed 
defaultfor 
default'vulnerable persons' or cases concerned with liberty
default.
default 
default  
defaultThus:
default* 
defaultAsylum seekers are included 
default 
defaultbut only while they are seeking asylu
defaultm
default;
default* Current immigration detainees are included 
defaultbut only while they remain detained, and only in relation to challenging the 
defaultfact of their detention
default.   Challenges to mistreatment in detention or discrimination in detention are therefore excluded.  'Tanja', whose case concerning sexual assaults by Serco officers at Yarl's Wood immigration removal centre was recently reported  in 
defaultthe 
defaultObserver
default 
defaultnewspaper
default  would not be eligible for legal aid in relation to such complaints.
default* Those who can show reasonable grounds that they are trafficking victims are included 
defaultbut only in rela
defaulttion to immigration claims, some 
defaultemployment claims and 
defaultdamages claims against the alleged trafficker
default.  In relation to any other advice or challenge (eg concerning eligibility for welfare benefits
default, community care
default or mental health support) 
defaultsuch a person 
defaultwould be out of scope.
default* Victims of domestic violence are i
defaultncluded 
defaultbut 
defaultagain only in relation to limited categories of claims
default.
default15.   Those who will be excluded from eligibility for legal aid (and hence access to justice) by the residence test include:
default* those who have suffered serious abuse of power by UK state ag
defaultents but who reside abroad (for example
default Baha Mousa'
defaults family, a person extraordinarily rendered to Guantanamo Bay
default);
default* children who have resided in the United Kingdom for most or all of their lives, and
default who would be eligible for formal leave to remain, but
default w
defaulthose parent
defaults
default 
defaulthave
default failed to regularise their immigration status
default.
default* children without parental support who cannot provide evidence of twelve months' lawful residence.
default*  disabled people and mentally ill people who cannot provide proof of twelve months' lawf
defaultul residence will be unable to access even emergency help.
default16.   There will 
defaultthus 
defaultbe categories of people who
default, irrespective of the extent of their needs or the merits of their case 
default are effectively outside the reach of the rule of law.
default   These people are di
defaultsproportionately likely to be female, or children, or disabled.  Yet the equality consequences of these proposals do not appear to have been considered adequately or at all.  T
defaulthey are likely to breach article
default 15 of the UN Convention on the Elimination o
defaultf D
defaultiscrimination Against Women and articles 12 and 13 of the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities.
default17.  Lest it be suggested that the 'exceptional funding' provisions under s10 LASPO provide an adequate safety net, it is clear that the exc
defaulteptional funding mechani
defaultsm does not work.   Section 10 LASPO
default provides a theoretical entitlement to assistance if failure to provide it would breach human rights or EU law rights.  However, 
defaultafter six months of the scheme's operation, research showed
default that only 233 applications have been received, and 
defaultof these only six had been granted.   The form is 17 pages long, and there is no funding for solicitors to complete it.  One street homeless man with learning difficulties was refused exceptional funding 
defaultto 
defaulthelp him 
defaultregularise his immigration status so as to enable him to become eligible for community care help
default.
default18.  Nor does it appear that the lacuna could be filled by a public interest body - such as Child Poverty Action Group or Medical Justice - could
default bring a representative claim in relation 
defaultto an area of wider public interest, since the parallel consultation 
defaultJudicial Review: Proposals for Further Reform 
default (06/09/2013) proposes removing standing from such bodies.
default19.  It is unlikely that the 
defaultintroductio
defaultn of a 
defaultresidence test will save money.  In addition to the costs of administering it, 
defaultthere are likely to be significant costs incurred by local authorities dealing with the destitute
default.  T
defaulthe likelihood is that there will be significantly more self-represen
defaultting litigants in the Administrative Court list.  The costs of this - to other litigants, 
defaultto the reputation of the British justice system, in creation of delays, and to the administration of courts - are enormous.    They do 
default not appear to have been factor
defaulted in to the ostensible costs savings.
default   See the observations of Lord Justice Ward in 
defaultWright v Michael Wright Supplies Ltd 
default [2013] EWCA Civ 234 at [2]:
default"What I find so depressing is that the case highlights the difficulties increasingly encountered by the 
defaultjudiciary at all levels when dealing with litigants in person. Two problems in particular are revealed. The first is how to bring order to the chaos which litigants in person invariably – and wholly understandably – manage to create in putting forward thei
defaultr claims and defences. Judges should not have to micro-manage cases, coaxing and cajoling the parties to focus on the issues that need to be resolved. Judge Thornton did a brilliant job in that regard yet, as this case shows, that can be disproportionately
default time-consuming. It may be saving the Legal Services Commission which no longer offers legal aid for this kind of litigation but saving expenditure in one public department in this instance simply increases it in the courts. The expense of three judges of 
defaultthe Court of Appeal dealing with this kind of appeal is enormous. The consequences by way of delay of other appeals which need to be heard are unquantifiable. The appeal would certainly never have occurred if the litigants had been represented. With more a
defaultnd more self-represented litigants, this problem is not going to go away. We may have to accept that we live in austere times, but as I come to the end of eighteen years service in this court, I shall not refrain from expressing my conviction that justice 
defaultwill be ill served indeed by this emasculation of legal aid.
default"
