defaultPRISONERSdefault20.  
defaultThe MOJ proposes removing  legal aid for a very wide variety of cases arising in prisons (even if internal complaints mechanisms/ombudsmen have not resolved them, even if the complaints are constitutionally important ones).  
defaultThe proposals for removing civi
defaultl legal aid for prisoners 
defaulthave 
defaultnot materially altered, save that the requirement to have a criminal legal aid contract for prison work has been removed.  
default21.   
defaultPrisoners
default 
defaultin the complete control of the state.  
defaultWithout legal aid, they are probably unable to
default obtain independent scrutiny of complaints against it.  
defaultRemoving 
defaultlegal aid to enable them to challenge state action, where other means of redress have failed, is 
defaulttherefore antithetical to the rule of law.  The suggestion that prisoners should use alternati
defaultve means of resolving grievances such as internal complaints and the Prisons and Probation Ombudsman does not obviate this concern, since judicial review has always been a 
defaultremedy of 
defaultlast resort, but 
defaultone which 
defaultsometimes 
defaultproves
default necessary. 
